<article class="content content--reading post">
  <a name="background"></a>
  <h1>Background</h1>

  <p>
    When I was leading Product Design at Grow Therapy, the company identified 
    <strong>intersession engagement</strong> as one of the most important 
    strategic priorities. We knew that to deliver better care, to 
    support providers in getting paid for their time, and demonstrate 
    outcomes strong enough to maintain and expand insurance contracts, 
    we had to improve the quality of care in general. 
    We could do this by helping clients engaging in personal reflections,
    activities provided by providers,
    and parparing for their upcoming session by capturing
    important insights and topics.
    <em>between sessions</em>.
  </p>

  <a name="team"></a>
  <h1>The Team</h1>

  <p>
    To make this real, I led design for a group that included <strong>Janice</strong>, 
    a staff designer; <strong>Prabha</strong>, a staff PM; and later, <strong>Sofia</strong>, 
    another designer who I pulled in for a specific strategy challenge. 
    On the product side, <strong>Mayuri</strong> was my key partner and 
    responsible for product side. My role as design leader became to 
    set the ambition, coach the designers and product managers to think 
    beyond narrow framing, and to secure executive alignment so the work 
    could land as a core company initiative.
  </p>

