<article class="content content--reading post">
  <p>
    When I reviewed this, I observed that the 
    <strong>solution space was centered around logistig; helping people who
    already refleced take their notes and make them easily accessible to their
    therapist.</strong>. 
    It solved for the easy case — clients who already reflected and took notes — 
    but not for the majority of clients who struggled most with reflection. 
    It ignored the people who froze when prompted, 
    who felt inhibited bringing up sensitive issues, 
    or who simply didn't have the habit of reflecting at all.
    I believe the problem they were solving for was an optimziation.
  </p>

  <p>
    I aligned with a Group PM, and together we agreed that the scope had to expand. 
    I took the lead and prompted the team to reframe their problem. I gave them
    some general direction to get them started:
    <em>How might we help people who don't know how to reflect? 
    How might we support those who don't have the habit of reflection?</em> 
    This reframing process eventually generated a much richer set of problem statements — 
    ones that were both more ambitious and more customer-centered.
  </p>

  <h2>Driving Exploration</h2>

  <p>
    Once the team had reframed the problems, They were able to break out of
    incremental solutioning. I worked directly with Janice during 
    the <strong>solution exploration </strong> phase to continue to keep 
    Janice a little more high level. Janice and Prabha would study 
    competitors for patterns in reflection and preparation, 
    to use AI tools like ChatGPT and Subframe to generate divergent ideas 
    and prototype and test with customers to validate not just 
    <em>whether</em> clients forgot topics, but <em>why reflection was 
    difficult in the first place</em> and what about these ideas
    worked for them.
  </p>

  <p>
    This push reframed the work and opened up a much more ambitious set of concepts.
    The team began exploring guided prompts pulled from past session 
    transcripts to help clients "pick up where they left off." 
    They tested visual reflection tools that allowed people to 
    sketch or draw instead of writing. They built guided categories 
    like <em>"Celebrate" → "a win at work"</em> or <em>"an 
    improvement in my relationship.
    "</em> They considered continuity prompts that nudged clients to build 
    on prior reflections rather than starting from scratch.
  </p>

  <p>
    By forcing the team to experiment with new methods and approaches, 
    I helped shift Session Topics from a narrow note-sharing tool into a
     set of solutions that addressed the needs of clients 
     who struggled to reflect as a habit.
  </p>
</article>

