<article class="content content--reading post">
  <h2>Championing Innovation (and Practicing Pragmatism)</h2>

  <p>
    One of the most ambitious directions I personally championed was 
    <strong>audio-first reflection</strong>. From our recent 
    acquisition of Summit (a life coach startup) I had learned 
    that their most engaged clients weren't the ones who chatted 
    with their AI life coach — they were the ones who spoke to it. 
    This supported my own hypothesis that reading and typing 
    text while reflecting inhibited free-flow expression, 
    whereas voice would unlock more authentic, natural reflection.
  </p>

  <p>
    I didn't leave this at gut instinct. I used 
    <strong>ChatGPT's Deep Research feature</strong> 
    and worked with my research partner Hannah to gather 
    evidence from external sources on how conversational 
    AI — particularly voice — could transform engagement. 
    I then brought this evidence to our Group PM and our CTO, 
    positioning audio-first not just as a feature idea, 
    but as a <strong>strategic differentiator</strong> 
    that could elevate Session Topics into something 
    uniquely valuable.
  </p>
</article>

