<article class="content content--reading post">
  <p>
    The CTO ultimately pushed back, arguing that testing audio 
    was expensive and wouldn't sway our decision to experiment
    with audio in general on a mobile app - he didn't field
    that experimenting now would yield insights relevant
    enough to justify the investment. 
    I disagreed, but I also knew when to adapt. 
    I committed to punting the standalone experiment 
    while continuing to push for audio-first reflection
    as part of the
    <strong>mobile app roadmap</strong>.
  </p>

  <p>
    This moment highlighted two aspects of my leadership: 
    my ability to <strong>champion innovation and scope 
    expansion</strong>, pushing Session Topics 
    beyond incremental improvements, 
    and my ability to <strong>practice pragmatism a
    nd alignment</strong>, showing that even when I disagreed, 
    I could commit to the organizational decision while preserving 
    the long-term vision. It was a win: 
    I broadened the scope of what Session Topics could mean strategically, 
    introduced evidence-backed innovation, 
    and kept the door open for future implementation.
  </p>

  <h2>Guiding Execution</h2>

  <p>
    As we continued toward the launch, 
    I worked closely with the team through multiple design reviews,
    alignment presentations, and design reviews.
    We iterated, refining both the 
    client experience and the provider workflow.
  </p>

  <p>
    Two interventions stand out:
  </p>

  <strong>AI Summarization</strong>
  <p>Rather than 
    limiting clients to short notes, 
    and focusing on people who already have the habit of reflection, 
    I pushed for open 
    reflections that we could then summarize with 
    AI into discrete topics. Providers now received 
    actionable summaries without being overwhelmed by raw text.</p>
  
  <strong>Dynamic Prompting Strategy</strong>
  <p>
    The team's original plan was to prompt clients 
    exactly twenty-four hours before a session. 
    I asked Janice to collaborate with Sofia to 
    rethink the strategy around the real client journey: 
    how long between selecting a therapist and their 
    first session, how long between recurring sessions, 
    and how to avoid fatigue by reducing prompts when a 
    client had already reflected. 
    This produced a smarter, 
    more contextual prompting system that 
    meaningfully improved engagement.</p>
