<article class="content content--reading post">
  <a name="impact"></a>
  <h1>The Impact</h1>

  <p>
    The launch seemed a success. 
    Clients engaged and providers valued 
    the clarity of AI-generated topics, 
    and most importantly, the initiative demonstrated that 
    <strong>intersession engagement was not only possible b
    ut powerful</strong>. It can advance care quality, 
    support providers, and create measurable outcomes 
    that Grow will be able to use to strengthen its 
    insurance partnerships.
  </p>

  <p>
    It also set a precedent. Session Topics will be the first 
    step to the proving ground that will validate intersession 
    engagement as a 
    <strong>pillar of Grow Therapy's product vision</strong>, 
    influencing how Grow will design the mobile app and 
    evolve their long-term Technical strategy.
  </p>

  <a name="reflection"></a>
  <h1>Reflection</h1>

  <p>
    This project was never just about a feature. 
    It was about recognizing when ambition was too small, 
    aligning with leadership to expand scope, 
    coaching a team into deeper exploration, 
    and pushing for bold, innovative ideas backed by evidence. 
    It was about navigating strategic pivots, 
    practicing pragmatism when needed, and still delivering impact.
  </p>

  <p>
    For me, Session Topics was a demonstration of
    design leadership at its fullest: setting strategy, c
    hampioning innovation, securing executive alignment, 
    and raising the bar for my team. 
    It showed how design can shape not just the product, 
    but the company's direction.
  </p>
</article>
